merican culture—from blackface minstrel shows to the works of William Shakespeare—into a battlefield in the war on insanity. Reiss also shows how asylums touched the lives and shaped the writing of key figures, such as Emerson and Poe, who viewed the system alternately as the fulfillment of a democratic ideal and as a kind of medical enslavement. Without neglecting this troubling contradiction, Theaters of Madness prompts us to reflect on what our society can learn from a generation that urgently and creatively tried to solve the problem of mental illness.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aHospitals in literaturexHistoryy19th century. 0aManners and customs. 0aMedicine in literature. 0aMentally ill, Writings of the, AmericanxHistory and criticism. 0aPsychiatric hospitalsxSocial aspectszUnited StatesxHistoryy19th century. 0aPsychiatric hospitalszUnited StatesxHistoryy19th century. 7aPSYCHOLOGY / General.2bisacsh  ainsane asylums, 19th century, american culture, united states of america, cultural studies, insanity, democracy, freedom, modernity, patients, mental illness, doctors, ralph waldo emerson, edgar allan poe, medical enslavement, contradiction, psychiatric hospital, social aspects, literature, literary representations, mentally ill, criticism, new york state, blackface, race, racism, gender, captivity, william shakespeare, minstrelsy, minstrel shows.40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226709659423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226709659/original  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles